@node "inst_usar" "Installing & Using"


    Put the executable where you think fits better.. (i personally prefer on
YAM:)

    The program will work with messages stored on Yam:Incoming directory.

    Since i'm not sure how Yam treats file locking/sharing, i suggest you
only execute this when Yam is not being executed.

    @{b}DO NOT EXECUTE THIS PROGRAM MORE THAN ONCE AT SAME TIME@{ub}, or it will fail
when creating temporary file (what's the point doing this, anyway?)



    Just double click the program and it will do all the job without the
need of any user intervention.
@endnode

@node "bugs" "Bugs/Limitations"
@{b}@{u}BUGS (or undesired features, as you prefer):@{ub}@{uu}


- When selecting the 'aglutinated' UU message on YAM, after long
  disk access, the window appears empty or appears only with the
  header text (from, to, subject, etc..). Saving the decoded UU
  is not possible. YAM may lock up if trying clicking around.
     @{b}This thing seems being a bug on YAM, something relationed to
  UU data processing (maybe because big sized UUs).@{ub}
  Solution: open the window and save text as 'original'. Decode
  the saved text using some external UU decoder.

- If the directory Yam:Incoming doesn't exist, i don't know what will
  happen (Lockout? Guru? Nothing? make your bet..) -- i have no patience
  now for including 'dumb-proof' features.

- If the program encounters a simple fractioned message that @{b}ISN'T@{ub}
  @{b}an UU-encoded file@{ub} (a text-only message containing "001 of 002" on
  topic, as example), the program will not loose control.. but the
  message will be damaged. -- BAH!! i just received this kind of
  thing once or twice and it was junk.



@{b}@{u}LIMITATIONS:@{ub}@{uu}


- once started it can't be stopped! - (great, huh?)
  if you're not sure, make a backup of YAM:Incoming first.

- the program will not update message subject on YAM index file.
  it means that when you browse messages in YAM you'll see something
  like this:
  "ftpserver job: BigFile.zip, Part 001 of 085" being the final
  aglutinated file.
  It's strange but there's no problems with this.

- maximum 65534 messages on directory (enough, isn't it?)
  maximum 64 splitted UU files processed per program execution
    (execute again if there's more..)
  maximum 255 parts per UU splitted file (around 12Mb of UU, if 50k blocks)

- duplicated file requests (same topic): the program @{b}MAY MIX@{ub}
  parts of different file requests @{b}IN THIS CASE@{ub}. If you made
  it using the same ftp-mail server and the same e-mail
  account, this is probably would cause no problem.
@endnode

